en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton_(unit)\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022 style=\u0022text-decoration:none;color:rgb(11,0,128);font-family:sans-serif;font-size:14.4444446563721px;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:normal;letter-spacing:normal;line-height:24.8888893127441px;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;word-spacing:0px;background:rgb(255,255,255) none;\u0022 title=\u0022Newton (unit)\u0022\u003EN\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022color:rgb(37,37,37);font-family:sans-serif;font-size:14.4444446563721px;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:normal;letter-spacing:normal;line-height:24.8888893127441px;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;word-spacing:0px;float:none;background-color:rgb(255,255,255);\u0022\u003E. After a period of one million years this would yield an imparted speed of 20\u00A0m/s, with a displacement from the original position of 0.03\u003Cspan\u003E\u00A0\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Light-year\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022 style=\u0022text-decoration:none;color:rgb(11,0,128);font-family:sans-serif;font-size:14.4444446563721px;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:normal;letter-spacing:normal;line-height:24.8888893127441px;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;word-spacing:0px;background:rgb(255,255,255) none;\u0022 title=\u0022Light-year\u0022\u003Elight-years\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022color:rgb(37,37,37);font-family:sans-serif;font-size:14.4444446563721px;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:normal;letter-spacing:normal;line-height:24.8888893127441px;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;word-spacing:0px;float:none;background-color:rgb(255,255,255);\u0022\u003E. After one billion years, the speed would be 20\u00A0km/s and the displacement 34,000 light-years, a little over a third of the estimated width of the\u003Cspan\u003E\u00A0\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milky_Way\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022 style=\u0022text-decoration:none;color:rgb(11,0,128);font-family:sans-serif;font-size:14.4444446563721px;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:normal;letter-spacing:normal;line-height:24.8888893127441px;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;word-spacing:0px;background:rgb(255,255,255) none;\u0022 title=\u0022Milky Way\u0022\u003EMilky Way\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022color:rgb(37,37,37);font-family:sans-serif;font-size:14.4444446563721px;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:normal;letter-spacing:normal;line-height:24.8888893127441px;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;word-spacing:0px;float:none;background-color:rgb(255,255,255);\u0022\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E\u00A0\u003C/span\u003Egalaxy.\u003C/span\u003E \u0022\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHow long would it take for a star like Vega or Sirius?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"kerbiloid","CreatedById":129408,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-13T16:56:19Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHow they will avoid the light pressure of other stars passing by?\u003Cbr\u003E\nOtherwise it will be a insane space papillon, larger a star, chaotically flying from star to star, crashing everything on its way..\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Spaceception","CreatedById":152800,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-13T17:02:14Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222953981\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022156394\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221487004979\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022129408\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022kerbiloid\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n4 minutes ago, kerbiloid said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHow they will avoid the light pressure of other stars passing by?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI don\u0027t think the light pressure of stars 10s if not 1000s of ly\u0027s away will affect it.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"kerbiloid","CreatedById":129408,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-13T17:03:56Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222953993\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022156394\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221487005334\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022152800\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Spaceception\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n1 minute ago, Spaceception said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI don\u0027t think the light pressure of stars 10s if not 1000s of ly\u0027s away will affect it.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nInside 16 ly there are 57 star systems.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222017-02-13T17:04:12Z\u0022 title=\u002202/13/2017 05:04  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00227 yr\u0022\u003EFebruary 13, 2017\u003C/time\u003E by kerbiloid\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Spaceception","CreatedById":152800,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-13T17:06:37Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222953996\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022156394\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221487005436\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022129408\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022kerbiloid\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\nJust now, kerbiloid said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nInside 16 ly there are 57 star systems.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBut they\u0027re separated by at least several ly, and the thruster wouldn\u0027t go past a few AU.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"p1t1o","CreatedById":74091,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-13T18:38:44Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222953978\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022156394\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221487004885\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022152800\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Spaceception\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n1 hour ago, Spaceception said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHow long would it take for a star like Vega or Sirius?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIf I recall my Mechanics correctly, the equation you want (for constant acceleration) is:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nS=UT\u002B0.5AT\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nWhere:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nS = Distance travelled in metres (ie: the distance from start position to star you want) in time T.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nU = initial velocity (zero - for all intents and purposes)\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nA = acceleration (in this case roughly 6*10\u003Csup\u003E-13\u003C/sup\u003E m/s)\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nT = Time in seconds taken to reach S\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSolve for T\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n(Because U=0 you can ignore the \u0022UT\u0022 term and treat the equation as S=0.5AT\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E)\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222953981\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022156394\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221487004979\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022129408\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022kerbiloid\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n1 hour ago, kerbiloid said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHow they will avoid the light pressure of other stars passing by?\u003Cbr\u003E\nOtherwise it will be a insane space papillon, larger a star, chaotically flying from star to star, crashing everything on its way..\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThis is where the inverse square law really helps us. The thruster is tens of thousands of times closer to its star than even another star just 1ly away (1ly = ~63kAU). The light pressure from a star 1ly will therefore be (63000\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E)-times less than that from a star 1AU away.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nA good way to visualise this is that gravity falls of in direct proportion to photon pressure, the thruster will be affected by the light from other stars about as much as it is affected by the gravity from other stars.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n***\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nNote that when considering travelling \u0022to other stars\u0022 using this thruster, it should be noted that stars can have quite high velocities between them (Gliese 445, the star that the Voyager probes will make a \u0022close\u0022 pass with in 40k years, is travelling *towards* us SIGNIFICANTLY faster than Voyager is *leaving* us. I think it is in the tens of km/s range. In other words, if your intention is to travel to other stars, your best bet is to wait here.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe travel one will be doing with this kind of thruster is not the \u0022lets visit [place]\u0022 kind of travel but more of a \u0022Where do we want our civilisation to be in 10 billion years relative to the galactic centre\u0022 or \u0022How would we like to alter the already-present trajectory of our star over the next few billion years.\u0022\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThis is not \u0022travel\u0022 as we normally consider it.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Spaceception","CreatedById":152800,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-13T19:06:39Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222954112\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022156394\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221487011124\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002274091\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022p1t1o\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n26 minutes ago, p1t1o said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nS = Distance travelled in metres (ie: the distance from start position to star you want) in time T.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThat\u0027s gonna be a lotta zeros.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"p1t1o","CreatedById":74091,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-13T19:32:12Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222954154\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022156394\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221487012799\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022152800\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Spaceception\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n24 minutes ago, Spaceception said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThat\u0027s gonna be a lotta zeros.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n15, 16, maybe 17 \u003Cimg alt=\u0022:)\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_smiley.gif\u0022 title=\u0022:)\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"kunok","CreatedById":147982,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-13T22:12:52Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe crazyness\u00A0 is high in that concept. I didn\u0027t know that one. I LIKE IT.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBut is so far from our technological level that we only could speculate, and I don\u0027t think it wont even be an educated guess\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"p1t1o","CreatedById":74091,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-14T08:42:12Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222954364\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022156394\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221487023972\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022147982\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022kunok\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n10 hours ago, kunok said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe crazyness\u00A0 is high in that concept. I didn\u0027t know that one. I LIKE IT.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBut is so far from our technological level that we only could speculate, and I don\u0027t think it wont even be an educated guess\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nYah. Its like someone saw a Dyson Sphere and thought \u0022Well.....thats \u003Cem\u003Equite\u003C/em\u003E impressive....\u0022\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"kerbiloid","CreatedById":129408,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-14T10:42:03Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nWe need to go deeper.\u003Cbr\u003E\nA megaship using the Milky Way blackhole (Sgr A*) as energy source and main booster.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Spaceception","CreatedById":152800,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-14T17:24:11Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222954830\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022156394\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221487068923\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022129408\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022kerbiloid\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n6 hours ago, kerbiloid said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nWe need to go deeper.\u003Cbr\u003E\nA megaship using the Milky Way blackhole (Sgr A*) as energy source and main booster.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv\u003E\n\u003Cdiv\u003E\n\u003Cdiv title=\u0022Protected by Grammarly\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv\u003E\n\u003Cdiv\u003E\n\u003Cdiv title=\u0022Protected by Grammarly\u0022\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThat probably wouldn\u0027t work. For several reasons.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nTake a look at page 15, there\u0027s a nice chart \u003Cimg alt=\u0022:)\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_smiley.gif\u0022 title=\u0022:)\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://arxiv.org/pdf/0908.1803.pdf\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://arxiv.org/pdf/0908.1803.pdf\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAnd who knows how hard it\u0027ll be to build a ship capable of traveling at even 0.01c that weighs 4 millions suns. \u003Cimg alt=\u0022:o\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/ZNGIcon2.png\u0022 title=\u0022:o\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222017-02-14T17:30:28Z\u0022 title=\u002202/14/2017 05:30  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00227 yr\u0022\u003EFebruary 14, 2017\u003C/time\u003E by Spaceception\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"kerbiloid","CreatedById":129408,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-14T17:33:12Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222955109\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022156394\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221487093051\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022152800\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Spaceception\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n10 minutes ago, Spaceception said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nTake a look at page 15, there\u0027s a nice chart \u003Cimg alt=\u0022:)\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_smiley.gif\u0022 title=\u0022:)\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://arxiv.org/pdf/0908.1803.pdf\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://arxiv.org/pdf/0908.1803.pdf\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThey speak about the blackhole evapouration.\u003Cbr\u003E\nBut I mean:\u003Cbr\u003E\n1) particle-antiparticle pairs which born in close proximity of its event horizon as a long-lasting energy source for equipment,\u003Cbr\u003E\n2) acceleration of a piece of matter splitting in two halves near the event horizon, when the second part falls down, for propulsion\u003Cbr\u003E\n3) also BH is a cheap way to fire thermonukes from occasional hydrogen clouds.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222017-02-14T17:35:09Z\u0022 title=\u002202/14/2017 05:35  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00227 yr\u0022\u003EFebruary 14, 2017\u003C/time\u003E by kerbiloid\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"}]}